[src:httpx-client/api] Only use these functions if you're testing HTTPX in a console or making a small number of requests.
[src:httpx-client/api] Using a `Client` will enable HTTP/2 and connection pooling for more efficient and long-lived connections.
[src:httpx-client/api] Note that the `data`, `files`, `json` and `content` parameters are not available on this function, as `GET` requests should not include a request body.
[src:httpx-client/api] Note that the `data`, `files`, `json` and `content` parameters are not available on this function, as `OPTIONS` requests should not include a request body.
[src:httpx-client/api] Note that the `data`, `files`, `json` and `content` parameters are not available on this function, as `HEAD` requests should not include a request body.
[src:httpx-client/api] Note that the `data`, `files`, `json` and `content` parameters are not available on this function, as `DELETE` requests should not include a request body.
[src:httpx-client/api] Alternative to `httpx.request()` that streams the response body instead of loading it into memory at once.
[src:httpx-client/api] An HTTP client, with connection pooling, HTTP/2, redirects, cookie persistence, etc.
[src:httpx-client/api] HTTP headers to include when sending requests.
[src:httpx-client/api] Cookie values to include when sending requests.
[src:httpx-client/api] Query parameters to include in the URL when sending requests.
[src:httpx-client/api] Authentication class used when none is passed at the request-level.
[src:httpx-client/api] See `Client.build_request()`, `Client.send()` and Merging of configuration for how the various parameters are merged with client-level configuration.
[src:httpx-client/api] Typically you'll want to build one with `Client.build_request()` so that any client-level configuration is merged into the request, but passing an explicit `httpx.Request()` is supported as well.
[src:httpx-client/api] An asynchronous HTTP client, with connection pooling, HTTP/2, redirects, cookie persistence, etc.
[src:httpx-client/api] See `AsyncClient.build_request()`, `AsyncClient.send()` and Merging of configuration for how the various parameters are merged with client-level configuration.
[src:httpx-client/api] Typically you'll want to build one with `AsyncClient.build_request()` so that any client-level configuration is merged into the request, but passing an explicit `httpx.Request()` is supported as well.
[src:httpx-client/async] HTTPX offers a standard synchronous API by default, but also gives you the option of an async client if you need it.
[src:httpx-client/async] Async is a concurrency model that is far more efficient than multi-threading, and can provide significant performance benefits and enable the use of long-lived network connections such as WebSockets.
[src:httpx-client/async] If you're working with an async web framework then you'll also want to use an async client for sending outgoing HTTP requests.
[src:httpx-client/async] To make asynchronous requests, you'll need an `AsyncClient`.
[src:httpx-client/async] Use IPython or Python 3.9+ with `python -m asyncio` to try this code interactively, as they support executing `async`/`await` expressions in the console.
[src:httpx-client/async] If you're using an async client then there are a few bits of API that use async methods.
[src:httpx-client/async] Use `async with httpx.AsyncClient()` if you want a context-managed client...
[src:httpx-client/async] In order to get the most benefit from connection pooling, make sure you're not instantiating multiple client instances - for example by using `async with` inside a "hot loop".
[src:httpx-client/async] This can be achieved either by having a single scoped client that's passed throughout wherever it's needed, or by having a single global client instance.
[src:httpx-client/async] The `AsyncClient.stream(method, url, ...)` method is an async context block.
[src:httpx-client/async] For situations when context block usage is not practical, it is possible to enter "manual mode" by sending a `Request` instance using `client.send(..., stream=True)`.
[src:httpx-client/async] When using this "manual streaming mode", it is your duty as a developer to make sure that `Response.aclose()` is called eventually.
[src:httpx-client/async] Failing to do so would leave connections open, most likely resulting in resource leaks down the line.
[src:httpx-client/async] When instantiating a transport instance directly, you need to use `httpx.AsyncHTTPTransport`.
[src:httpx-client/async] HTTPX supports either `asyncio` or `trio` as an async environment.
[src:httpx-client/async] It will auto-detect which of those two to use as the backend for socket operations and concurrency primitives.
[src:httpx-client/async] AsyncIO is Python's built-in library for writing concurrent code with the async/await syntax.
[src:httpx-client/async] Trio is an alternative async library, designed around the the principles of structured concurrency.
[src:httpx-client/async] The `trio` package must be installed to use the Trio backend.
[src:httpx-client/async] AnyIO is an asynchronous networking and concurrency library that works on top of either `asyncio` or `trio`.
[src:httpx-client/async] It blends in with native libraries of your chosen backend (defaults to `asyncio`).
[src:httpx-client/async] For details on calling directly into ASGI applications, see the `ASGITransport` docs.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] In software engineering, a **connection pool** is a cache of reusable database connections managed by the client or middleware.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] It reduces the overhead of opening and closing connections, improving performance and scalability in database applications.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] SQL databases typically use stateful, binary protocols that maintain session-specific information, such as transaction states and prepared statements, necessitating optimized connection pooling to minimize the overhead of repeatedly establishing connections.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Conversely, many mainstream NoSQL databases, like Azure Cosmos DB and Amazon DynamoDB, utilize stateless, HTTP-based protocols that handle each request independently.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] This architecture often reduces the need for traditional connection pooling, though reusing established connections can still offer performance benefits in high-throughput scenarios by avoiding the overhead of connection creation.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] In database environments, connection limits are typically determined by service tiers or resource configurations.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Azure SQL Database defines connection limits based on the selected tier, while Azure SQL Managed Instance enforces limits based on allocated resources, such as CPU, memory, or vCores.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] When connection pool configurations exceed these limits, issues such as rejected connections, throttling, or degraded performance can occur.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Depending on how database limits are applied, overprovisioned connection pools can create significant resource contention as the server struggles to manage excessive simultaneous connections.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Idle connections may encounter issues due to network conditions, such as NAT timeouts or dropped connections, or database state changes, such as session invalidation or transaction timeouts, potentially triggering reconnection processes that introduce additional overhead and performance penalties.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Over-provisioned pools can overwhelm server resources, causing increased latency and degraded system performance.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Token-based authentication mechanisms, such as Azure AD authentication, may affect connection pooling due to token expiration.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Expired tokens can invalidate connections within the pool, interrupting reuse.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] This behavior is observed in both cloud-based and on-premises database systems that implement modern authentication protocols.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] The efficiency of connection pooling can be influenced by network latency and endpoint configurations.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Public endpoints, commonly used in cloud-hosted databases, often introduce higher latency compared to private or direct connections.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] In environments with dynamic IP addressing, such as those involving cloud-native applications, disruptions in connection reuse may occur if firewall rules are not synchronized with changing IP addresses.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Databases that enforce TLS encryption, including those deployed in cloud and on-premises environments, require alignment between encryption settings and connection configurations.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] For example, the absence of encryption parameters in connection strings can lead to connection failures, rendering the pool ineffective.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Private endpoints and custom DNS configurations can create challenges for connection pooling.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Inconsistent or misconfigured DNS settings may delay or block connection establishment, affecting the performance and efficiency of connection reuse.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] This is particularly notable in environments with hybrid or private cloud setups.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] In modern cloud architectures like AWS, effective connection pooling management is critical for optimizing performance, scalability, and resource utilization.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Improper handling of connections can lead to bottlenecks and operational inefficiencies.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Containerized Environments: Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) containers maintain open database connections for their lifecycle.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Without connection pooling mechanisms (e.g., HikariCP, pgbouncer), idle or excessive connections can strain database resources.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Virtual Machine-Based Environments: AWS EC2 instances scale connection demand with the number of instances.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Manual or automated tuning of connection pool parameters is essential to prevent exceeding database limits.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] This ecosystem of tools and services empowers architects to design highly scalable and efficient applications while minimizing connection management overhead.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Azure SQL Database, Azure SQL Managed Instance, and SQL Server on virtual machines rely on client-side connection pooling implemented by libraries such as ADO.NET and JDBC.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] The database engine does not manage pooling, as it is entirely handled at the client level.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] Environmental factors, including service-tier limits in Azure SQL Database and resource constraints in Managed Instance, may indirectly affect pooling performance.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] In Azure Cosmos DB, connection pooling is managed at the SDK level rather than by the database service itself.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] SDKs such as those for .NET, Java, and Python implement connection pooling to reuse HTTP connections to the database endpoint, optimizing resource usage and performance.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] This functionality applies to all Cosmos DB account types, including provisioned throughput and serverless models.
[src:httpx-client/connection-pool] The stateless, HTTP-based architecture of Cosmos DB facilitates scalable and concurrent operations without the limitations typically associated with traditional connection pooling mechanisms.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] The standardization effort was supported by the Chrome, Opera, Firefox, Internet Explorer 11, Safari, Amazon Silk, and Edge browsers.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Most major browsers had added HTTP/2 support by the end of 2015.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] About 97% of web browsers used have the capability (and 100% of "tracked desktop" web browsers).
[src:httpx-client/http-2] As of July 2023, 36% (after topping out at just over 50%) of the top 10 million websites support HTTP/2.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Its successor is HTTP/3, a major revision that builds on the concepts established by HTTP/2.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] The changes do not require any changes to how existing web applications work, but new applications can take advantage of new features for increased speed.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] HTTP/2 leaves all of HTTP/1.1's high-level semantics, such as methods, status codes, header fields, and URIs, the same.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] What is new is how the data is framed and transported between the client and the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Websites that are efficient minimize the number of requests required to render an entire page by minifying (reducing the amount of code and packing smaller pieces of code into bundles, without reducing its ability to function) resources such as images and scripts.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] However, minification is not necessarily convenient nor efficient and may still require separate HTTP connections to get the page and the minified resources.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] HTTP/2 allows the server to "push" content, that is, to respond with data for more queries than the client requested.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] This allows the server to supply data it knows a web browser will need to render a web page, without waiting for the browser to examine the first response, and without the overhead of an additional request cycle.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Additional performance improvements in the first draft of HTTP/2 (which was a copy of SPDY) come from multiplexing of requests and responses to avoid some of the head-of-line blocking problem in HTTP 1 (even when HTTP pipelining is used), header compression, and prioritization of requests.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] However, as HTTP/2 runs on top of a single TCP connection, there is still potential for head-of-line blocking to occur if TCP packets are lost or delayed in transmission.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] HTTP/2 no longer supports HTTP/1.1's chunked transfer encoding mechanism, as it provides its own, more efficient mechanisms for data streaming.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] SPDY (pronounced like "speedy") was a previous HTTP-replacement protocol developed by a research project spearheaded by Google.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Primarily focused on reducing latency, SPDY uses the same TCP pipe but different protocols to accomplish this reduction.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] The basic changes made to HTTP/1.1 to create SPDY included "true request pipelining without FIFO restrictions, message framing mechanism to simplify client and server development, mandatory compression (including headers), priority scheduling, and even bi-directional communication".
[src:httpx-client/http-2] The HTTP Working Group considered Google's SPDY protocol, Microsoft's HTTP Speed+Mobility proposal (SPDY based), and Network-Friendly HTTP Upgrade.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] In July 2012, Facebook provided feedback on each of the proposals and recommended HTTP/2 be based on SPDY.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] The initial draft of HTTP/2 was published in November 2012 and was based on a straight copy of SPDY.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] The biggest difference between HTTP/1.1 and SPDY was that each user action in SPDY is given a "stream ID", meaning there is a single TCP channel connecting the user to the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] SPDY split requests into either control or data, using a "simple to parse binary protocol with two types of frames".
[src:httpx-client/http-2] SPDY showed evident improvement over HTTP, with a new page load speedup ranging from 11% to 47%.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] The development of HTTP/2 used SPDY as a jumping-off point.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Among the many detailed differences between the protocols, the most notable is that HTTP/2 uses a fixed Huffman code-based header compression algorithm, instead of SPDY's dynamic stream-based compression.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] This helps to reduce the potential for compression oracle attacks on the protocol, such as the CRIME attack.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] On February 9, 2015, Google announced plans to remove support for SPDY in Chrome in favor of support for HTTP/2.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] This took effect starting with Chrome 51.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] HTTP/2 is defined for both HTTP URIs (without TLS encryption, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2c**) and HTTPS URIs (over TLS using ALPN extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2**).
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Although the standard itself does not require usage of encryption, all major client implementations (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Opera, Safari) have stated they will only support HTTP/2 over TLS, which makes encryption de facto mandatory.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] The FreeBSD and Varnish developer Poul-Henning Kamp asserts that the standard was prepared on an unrealistically short schedule, ruling out any basis for the new HTTP/2 other than the SPDY protocol and resulting in other missed opportunities for improvement.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Kamp criticizes the protocol itself for being inconsistent and having needless, overwhelming complexity.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] He also states that the protocol violates the protocol layering principle, for example by duplicating flow control that belongs in the transport layer (TCP).
[src:httpx-client/http-2] He also suggested that the new protocol should have removed HTTP Cookies, introducing a breaking change.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Initially, some members of the Working Group tried to introduce an encryption requirement in the protocol.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Critics stated that encryption has non-negligible computing costs and that many HTTP applications actually have no need for encryption and their providers have no desire to spend additional resources on it.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Encryption proponents have stated that this encryption overhead is negligible in practice.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Poul-Henning Kamp has criticized the IETF for hastily standardizing Google's SPDY prototype as HTTP/2 due to political considerations.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] In the end the Working Group did not reach consensus over the mandatory encryption, although most client implementations require it, which makes encryption a *de facto* requirement.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] The HTTP/2 protocol also faced criticism for not supporting opportunistic encryption, a measure against passive monitoring similar to the STARTTLS mechanism that has long been available in other Internet protocols like SMTP.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] Critics have stated that the HTTP/2 proposal goes in violation of IETF's own RFC 7258 "Pervasive Monitoring Is an Attack", which also has a status of Best Current Practice 188.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] RFC7258/BCP188 mandates that pervasive monitoring be considered as an attack, and protocols designed by IETF should take steps to protect against passive monitoring (for example, through the use of opportunistic encryption).
[src:httpx-client/http-2] A number of specifications for opportunistic encryption of HTTP/2 have been provided, of which draft-nottingham-http2-encryption was adopted as an official work item of the working group, leading to the publication of RFC 8164 in May 2017.
[src:httpx-client/http-2] This head-of-line blocking in HTTP/2 is now widely regarded as a design flaw, and much of the effort behind QUIC and HTTP/3 has been devoted to reduce head-of-line blocking issues.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] include the representation data in the body.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The following is a request with no body.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:httpx-client/http-message-body] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The principal motivations for HTTPS are authentication of the accessed website and protection of the privacy and integrity of the exchanged data while it is in transit.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] It protects against man-in-the-middle attacks, and the bidirectional block cipher encryption of communications between a client and server protects the communications against eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The authentication aspect of HTTPS requires a trusted third party to sign server-side digital certificates.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This was historically an expensive operation, which meant fully authenticated HTTPS connections were usually found only on secured payment transaction services and other secured corporate information systems on the World Wide Web.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] In 2016, a campaign by the Electronic Frontier Foundation with the support of web browser developers led to the protocol becoming more prevalent.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTPS has since 2018 been used more often by web users than non-secure HTTP, primarily to protect page authenticity on all types of websites, secure accounts, and keep user communications, identity, and web browsing private.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) scheme *HTTPS* has identical usage syntax to the HTTP scheme.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] However, HTTPS signals the browser to use an added encryption layer of SSL/TLS to protect the traffic.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] SSL/TLS is especially suited for HTTP, since it can provide some protection even if only one side of the communication is authenticated.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This is the case with HTTP transactions over the Internet, where typically only the server is authenticated (by the client examining the server's certificate).
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTPS creates a secure channel over an insecure network.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This ensures reasonable protection from eavesdroppers and man-in-the-middle attacks, provided that adequate cipher suites are used and that the server certificate is verified and trusted.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Because HTTPS piggybacks HTTP entirely on top of TLS, the entirety of the underlying HTTP protocol can be encrypted.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This includes the request's URL, query parameters, headers, and cookies (which often contain identifying information about the user).
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] However, because website addresses and port numbers are necessarily part of the underlying TCP/IP protocols, HTTPS cannot protect their disclosure.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Web browsers know how to trust HTTPS websites based on certificate authorities that come pre-installed in their software.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Certificate authorities are in this way being trusted by web browser creators to provide valid certificates.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTPS is especially important over insecure networks and networks that may be subject to tampering.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Insecure networks, such as public Wi-Fi access points, allow anyone on the same local network to packet-sniff and discover sensitive information not protected by HTTPS.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Additionally, some free-to-use and paid WLAN networks have been observed tampering with webpages by engaging in packet injection in order to serve their own ads on other websites.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This practice can be exploited maliciously in many ways, such as by injecting malware onto webpages and stealing users' private information.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTPS is also important for connections over the Tor network, as malicious Tor nodes could otherwise damage or alter the contents passing through them in an insecure fashion and inject malware into the connection.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This is one reason why the Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Tor Project started the development of HTTPS Everywhere, which is included in Tor Browser.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] As more information is revealed about global mass surveillance and criminals stealing personal information, the use of HTTPS security on all websites is becoming increasingly important regardless of the type of Internet connection being used.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Even though metadata about individual pages that a user visits might not be considered sensitive, when aggregated it can reveal a lot about the user and compromise the user's privacy.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Deploying HTTPS also allows the use of HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 (and their predecessors SPDY and QUIC), which are new HTTP versions designed to reduce page load times, size, and latency.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] It is recommended to use HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) with HTTPS to protect users from man-in-the-middle attacks, especially SSL stripping.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTPS should not be confused with the seldom-used Secure HTTP (S-HTTP) specified in RFC 2660.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] As of April 2018, 33.2% of Alexa top 1,000,000 websites use HTTPS as default and 70% of page loads (measured by Firefox Telemetry) use HTTPS.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] As of June 2025, 71.2% of the Internet's 150,000 most popular websites have a secure implementation of HTTPS (up from 58.4% in December 2022), However, despite TLS 1.3's release in 2018, adoption has been slow, with many still remaining on the older TLS 1.2 protocol.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Most browsers display a warning if they receive an invalid certificate.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Older browsers, when connecting to a site with an invalid certificate, would present the user with a dialog box asking whether they wanted to continue.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Newer browsers display a warning across the entire window.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Newer browsers also prominently display the site's security information in the address bar.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Extended validation certificates show the legal entity on the certificate information.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Most browsers also display a warning to the user when visiting a site that contains a mixture of encrypted and unencrypted content.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Additionally, many web filters return a security warning when visiting prohibited websites.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, opining that "In an ideal world, every web request could be defaulted to HTTPS", has provided an add-on called HTTPS Everywhere for Mozilla Firefox, Google Chrome, Chromium, and Android, which enables HTTPS by default for hundreds of frequently used websites.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Forcing a web browser to load only HTTPS content has been supported in Firefox starting in version 83.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Starting in version 94, Google Chrome is able to "always use secure connections" if toggled in the browser's settings.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Prior to version 117, Google Chrome displayed a lock icon in the address bar, which has since been replaced by a "tune" icon.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Many users believe that a lock icon implies a website is safe, ignoring other security concerns.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The security of HTTPS is that of the underlying TLS, which typically uses long-term public and private keys to generate a short-term session key, which is then used to encrypt the data flow between the client and the server.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] X.509 certificates are used to authenticate the server (and sometimes the client as well).
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] As a consequence, certificate authorities and public key certificates are necessary to verify the relation between the certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] While this can be more beneficial than verifying the identities via a web of trust, the 2013 mass surveillance disclosures drew attention to certificate authorities as a potential weak point allowing man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] An important property in this context is forward secrecy, which ensures that encrypted communications recorded in the past cannot be retrieved and decrypted should long-term secret keys or passwords be compromised in the future.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Not all web servers provide forward secrecy.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] For HTTPS to be effective, a site must be completely hosted over HTTPS.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Additionally, cookies on a site served through HTTPS must have the secure attribute enabled.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] On a site that has sensitive information on it, the user and the session will get exposed every time that site is accessed with HTTP instead of HTTPS.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTPS URLs begin with "https://" and use port 443 by default, whereas HTTP URLs begin with "http://" and use port 80 by default.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTP is not encrypted and thus is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle and eavesdropping attacks, which can let attackers gain access to website accounts and sensitive information, and modify webpages to inject malware or advertisements.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTPS is designed to withstand such attacks and is considered secure against them (with the exception of HTTPS implementations that use deprecated versions of SSL).
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTP operates at the highest layer of the TCP/IP model—the application layer; as does the TLS security protocol (operating as a lower sublayer of the same layer), which encrypts an HTTP message prior to transmission and decrypts a message upon arrival.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Strictly speaking, HTTPS is not a separate protocol, but refers to the use of ordinary HTTP over an encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTPS encrypts all message contents, including the HTTP headers and the request/response data.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] With the exception of the possible CCA cryptographic attack described in the limitations section below, an attacker should at most be able to discover that a connection is taking place between two parties, along with their domain names and IP addresses.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] To prepare a web server to accept HTTPS connections, the administrator must create a public key certificate for the web server.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This certificate must be signed by a trusted certificate authority for the web browser to accept it without warning.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The authority certifies that the certificate holder is the operator of the web server that presents it.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Web browsers are generally distributed with a list of signing certificates of major certificate authorities so that they can verify certificates signed by them.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] A number of commercial certificate authorities exist, offering paid-for SSL/TLS certificates of a number of types, including Extended Validation Certificates.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Let's Encrypt, launched in April 2016, provides free and automated service that delivers basic SSL/TLS certificates to websites.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] According to the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Let's Encrypt will make switching from HTTP to HTTPS "as easy as issuing one command, or clicking one button." The majority of web hosts and cloud providers now leverage Let's Encrypt, providing free certificates to their customers.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The system can also be used for client authentication in order to limit access to a web server to authorized users.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] To do this, the site administrator typically creates a certificate for each user, which the user loads into their browser.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Normally, the certificate contains the name and e-mail address of the authorized user and is automatically checked by the server on each connection to verify the user's identity, potentially without even requiring a password.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] An important property in this context is perfect forward secrecy (PFS).
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Possessing one of the long-term asymmetric secret keys used to establish an HTTPS session should not make it easier to derive the short-term session key to then decrypt the conversation, even at a later time.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Diffie–Hellman key exchange (DHE) and Elliptic-curve Diffie–Hellman key exchange (ECDHE) are in 2013 the only schemes known to have that property.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] In 2013, only 30% of Firefox, Opera, and Chromium Browser sessions used it, and nearly 0% of Apple's Safari and Microsoft Internet Explorer sessions.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] TLS 1.3, published in August 2018, dropped support for ciphers without forward secrecy.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] As of February 2019, 96.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 52.1% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] As of July 2023, 99.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 75.2% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, for example because the secrecy of the private key has been compromised.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Newer versions of popular browsers such as Firefox, Opera, and Internet Explorer on Windows Vista implement the Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) to verify that this is not the case.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The browser sends the certificate's serial number to the certificate authority or its delegate via OCSP (Online Certificate Status Protocol) and the authority responds, telling the browser whether the certificate is still valid or not.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The CA may also issue a CRL to tell people that these certificates are revoked.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] CRLs are no longer required by the CA/Browser forum, nevertheless, they are still widely used by the CAs.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Most revocation statuses on the Internet disappear soon after the expiration of the certificates.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) and TLS (Transport Layer Security) encryption can be configured in two modes: *simple* and *mutual*.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] In simple mode, authentication is only performed by the server.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The mutual version requires the user to install a personal client certificate in the web browser for user authentication.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] In either case, the level of protection depends on the correctness of the implementation of the software and the cryptographic algorithms in use.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] SSL/TLS does not prevent the indexing of the site by a web crawler, and in some cases the URI of the encrypted resource can be inferred by knowing only the intercepted request/response size.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This allows an attacker to have access to the plaintext (the publicly available static content), and the encrypted text (the encrypted version of the static content), permitting a cryptographic attack.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Because TLS operates at a protocol level below that of HTTP and has no knowledge of the higher-level protocols, TLS servers can only strictly present one certificate for a particular address and port combination.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] In the past, this meant that it was not feasible to use name-based virtual hosting with HTTPS.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] A solution called Server Name Indication (SNI) exists, which sends the hostname to the server before encrypting the connection, although older browsers do not support this extension.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Support for SNI is available since Firefox 2, Opera 8, Apple Safari 2.1, Google Chrome 6, and Internet Explorer 7 on Windows Vista.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] A sophisticated type of man-in-the-middle attack called SSL stripping was presented at the 2009 Blackhat Conference.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The attacker then communicates in clear with the client.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This prompted the development of a countermeasure in HTTP called HTTP Strict Transport Security.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] HTTPS has been shown to be vulnerable to a range of traffic analysis attacks.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Traffic analysis attacks are a type of side-channel attack that relies on variations in the timing and size of traffic in order to infer properties about the encrypted traffic itself.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Traffic analysis is possible because SSL/TLS encryption changes the contents of traffic, but has minimal impact on the size and timing of traffic.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] In May 2010, a research paper by researchers from Microsoft Research and Indiana University discovered that detailed sensitive user data can be inferred from side channels such as packet sizes.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The researchers found that, despite HTTPS protection in several high-profile, top-of-the-line web applications in healthcare, taxation, investment, and web search, an eavesdropper could infer the illnesses/medications/surgeries of the user, his/her family income, and investment secrets.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The fact that most modern websites, including Google, Yahoo!, and Amazon, use HTTPS causes problems for many users trying to access public Wi-Fi hot spots, because a captive portal Wi-Fi hot spot login page fails to load if the user tries to open an HTTPS resource.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Several websites, such as NoSSL.sh, guarantee that they will always remain accessible by HTTP.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Netscape Communications created HTTPS in 1994 for its Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Originally, HTTPS was used with the SSL protocol.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] The original SSL protocol was developed by Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] As SSL evolved into Transport Layer Security (TLS), HTTPS was formally specified by RFC 2818 in May 2000.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] Google announced in February 2018 that its Chrome browser would mark HTTP sites as "Not Secure" after July 2018.
[src:httpx-client/hypertext-transfer-protocol-secure] This move was to encourage website owners to implement HTTPS, as an effort to make the World Wide Web more secure.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] HTTPX will automatically handle decoding the response content into Unicode text.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] You can inspect what encoding will be used to decode the response.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] In some cases the response may not contain an explicit encoding, in which case HTTPX will attempt to automatically determine an encoding to use.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] If you need to override the standard behaviour and explicitly set the encoding to use, then you can do that too.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] Any `gzip` and `deflate` HTTP response encodings will automatically be decoded for you.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] If `brotlipy` is installed, then the `brotli` response encoding will be supported.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] If `zstandard` is installed, then `zstd` response encodings will also be supported.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] Often Web API responses will be encoded as JSON.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] Some types of HTTP requests, such as `POST` and `PUT` requests, can include data in the request body.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] One common way of including that is as form-encoded data, which is used for HTML forms.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] Form encoded data can also include multiple values from a given key.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] Form encoded data is okay if all you need is a simple key-value data structure.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] For more complicated data structures you'll often want to use JSON encoding instead.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] For other encodings, you should use the `content=...` parameter, passing either a `bytes` type or a generator that yields `bytes`.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] You may also want to set a custom `Content-Type` header when uploading binary data.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] HTTPX also includes an easy shortcut for accessing status codes by their text phrase.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] Any successful response codes will return the `Response` instance rather than raising an exception.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] The method returns the response instance, allowing you to use it inline.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] The response headers are available as a dictionary-like interface.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] The `Headers` data type is case-insensitive, so you can use any capitalization.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] For large downloads you may want to use streaming responses that do not load the entire response body into memory at once.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] You can stream the binary content of the response...
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] Or stream the text, on a line-by-line basis...
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] HTTPX will use universal line endings, normalising all cases to `\n`.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] In some cases you might want to access the raw bytes on the response without applying any HTTP content decoding.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] In this case any content encoding that the web server has applied such as `gzip`, `deflate`, `brotli`, or `zstd` will not be automatically decoded.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] If you're using streaming responses in any of these ways then the `response.content` and `response.text` attributes will not be available, and will raise errors if accessed.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] Cookies are returned in a `Cookies` instance, which is a dict-like data structure with additional API for accessing cookies by their domain or path.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] By default, HTTPX will **not** follow redirects for all HTTP methods, although this can be explicitly enabled.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] For example, GitHub redirects all HTTP requests to HTTPS.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] The `history` property of the response can be used to inspect any followed redirects.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] It contains a list of any redirect responses that were followed, in the order in which they were made.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] HTTPX defaults to including reasonable timeouts for all network operations, meaning that if a connection is not properly established then it should always raise an error rather than hanging indefinitely.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] The default timeout for network inactivity is five seconds.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] You can also disable the timeout behavior completely...
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] For advanced timeout management, see Timeout fine-tuning.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] HTTPX supports Basic and Digest HTTP authentication.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] To provide credentials for Digest authentication you'll need to instantiate a `DigestAuth` object with the plaintext username and password as arguments.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] HTTPX will raise exceptions if an error occurs.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] The most important exception classes in HTTPX are `RequestError` and `HTTPStatusError`.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] The `RequestError` class is a superclass that encompasses any exception that occurs while issuing an HTTP request.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] These exceptions include a `.request` attribute.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] The `HTTPStatusError` class is raised by `response.raise_for_status()` on responses which are not a 2xx success code.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] These exceptions include both a `.request` and a `.response` attribute.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] There is also a base class `HTTPError` that includes both of these categories, and can be used to catch either failed requests, or 4xx and 5xx responses.
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] You can either use this base class to catch both categories...
[src:httpx-client/quickstart] For a full list of available exceptions, see Exceptions (API Reference).
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:httpx-client/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
